<div id="main_content">
	<h2>'Shaken and Unsettled' About Race</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date"></span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE198/en_US/040305west.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>Author Cornel West as part of the President's Eminent Scholars Series.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004112faeca0fb2b47ccbe006e68">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=0024004112faeca0fb2b47ccbe006e68"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			Fifty years after the U.S. Supreme Court issued a decision that led to the integration of public schools, theres still "a whole lot of de-facto segregation at work" and Americans still dont like to think deeply or talk publicly about race, Princeton University professor Cornel West said Thursday.    But students and others need to think critically about race and question some of the assumptions theyve held while "living in a white supremacist democracy," West said in a packed Pegasus Ballroom in the UCF Student Union.    "Every American whos concerned about the future of democracy needs to be shaken and unsettled at least for an instant in that way," West said.    Wests presentation, part of the UCF Presidents Eminent Scholars Series, was one of many spring events at UCF and other Orange County venues commemorating the 50th anniversary of the Supreme Courts Brown v. Board decision. The Florida Humanities Council helped to sponsor Wests speech.    West, the author or editor of more than 20 books about race, philosophy and religion, said the Brown v. Board decision was "just the beginning of the unraveling of the American apartheid." Many schools throughout the South, including those in Orange County, were not integrated until 10 or more years later. Blacks still were openly treated as inferior on buses and in restaurants.    "They did break the back of Jim Crow beginning with Brown v. Board, but Jim Crow Jr.s still around," West said.  One student asked West if he thought blacks were better off before Brown v. Board than they are today. West said its clear that middle- and upper-class blacks are better off, as poverty rates have declined dramatically in the past 50 years and life expectancy has increased, but many problems remain, especially for poorer blacks.    West also compared reactions to the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks with how blacks reacted to attacks on them in the 1950s and 1960s. The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and others talked about love and justice even after blacks were murdered by whites in the 50s and 60s. If they had responded like the United States did after Sept. 11, "there would have been a civil war again," he said.    West discussed the crisis in Haiti while answering questions from the audience. He faulted the Bush administration for turning its back on Haitian president Jean-Bertrand Aristide, who was democratically elected, and allowing "terrorists" to undermine him.     "I think that its deeply racist to turn back people who are of African descent running from killing fields, if in other contexts, there are others who are not black running from killing fields, and we embrace them," he added.    West also blamed Democrats for how theyve handled past crises, saying that both parties cater too much to the interests of "corporate elites."    The Brown v. Board series continues on Sunday, March 7, when the Sunflower County Freedom Project will perform an original play about a boys death that fueled the civil rights movement. The group will perform at 11:30 a.m. at the New Covenant Baptist Church of Orlando, 2210 S. Rio Grande Ave.    On Monday, March 15, Chicago Tribune columnist Clarence Page and St. Petersburg Times Editor Emeritus Eugene Patterson will speak about the role of the press in the civil rights movement. They will speak at 10 a.m. in the Pegasus Ballroom at the UCF Student Union. Workshops for professional and student journalists will be held that afternoon.    For more information and a complete schedule, visit www.brownblackandwhite.org. To participate in a discussion board about Brown v. Board and its impact, go to www.wmfe.org/bboards/display_forum_topics.asp?ForumID=10.    -UCF-          
		
	
